{"title_page": "Ro\u0219iorii de Vede", "text_new": "{{Redirect|Ro\u0219iori|other uses|Ro\u0219iori (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox Romanian subdivision\n|type                   = municipality\n|county                 = Teleorman\n|population_total       = auto\n|map_caption            = Location in Teleorman County\n| official_name          = Ro\u0219iorii de Vede\n| image_shield           = ROU TR Rosiorii de Vede CoA2.jpg\n| image_map              = Rosiori de Vede jud Teleorman.png\n| coordinates            = {{coord|44|6|41|N|24|59|39|E|region:RO|display=inline,title}}\n| leader_party           = PSD\n| leader_name            = Gheorghe-Valeric\u0103 C\u00e2rciumaru<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.2016bec.ro/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/SIAL2016_P_Lista_Moc-2.xlsx |title=Results of the 2016 local elections |publisher=Central Electoral Bureau |accessdate=2020-04-03 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n| area_total_km2         = \n| website                = {{url|http://www.primariarosioriidevede.ro/}}\n}}\n\n'''Ro\u0219iorii de Vede''' ({{IPA-ro|ro\u0283i\u02ccorij de \u02c8vede}}; sometimes '''Ro\u0219iori de Vede''' or, in old versions, '''Ru\u0219ii de Vede''') is a [[municipiu|city]] in [[Teleorman County]], [[Romania]]. Located in the [[Wallachia]] region, it is one of the oldest cities in the country. It was first mentioned in a document which dates back to 1385, when the city was visited by two [[List of states in the Holy Roman Empire|German]] [[pilgrim]]s who were returning from [[Jerusalem]] and stopped for a few days in a town they called ''Russenart''.{{citation needed|date=December 2010}}\n\nSeveral Romanian personalities were born in and around the city, such as [[Iulian Miu]], [[Radu Gr\u0103m\u0103ticu]], [[Alexandru Dep\u0103r\u0103\u021beanu]], [[Gala Galaction]], [[Petru Bellu]], [[Zaharia Stancu]], [[Marin Preda]] and [[Viorica D\u0103ncil\u0103]].\n\n{{Historical populations\n| source = Census data\n| 1912 |10960\n| 1930 |11453\n| 1948 |14905\n| 1956 |17320\n| 1966 |21747\n| 1977 |28847\n| 1992 |37640\n| 2002 |31873\n| 2011 |24222\n}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Ro\u0219iorii de Vede}}\n* [http://www.primariarosioriidevede.ro/ Ro\u0219iori de Vede City Hall site]\n* [http://www.rosioriidevedeonline.3owl.com/ Ro\u0219iori de Vede Community site]{{dead link|date=April 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n\n{{Teleorman County}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rosiorii De Vede}}\n[[Category:Cities in Romania]]\n[[Category:Populated places in Teleorman County]]\n\n\n{{Teleorman-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Redirect|Ro\u0219iori|other uses|Ro\u0219iori (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox Romanian subdivision\n|type                   = municipality\n|county                 = Teleorman\n|population_total       = auto\n|map_caption            = Location in Teleorman County\n| official_name          = Ro\u0219iorii de Vede\n| image_shield           = ROU TR Rosiorii de Vede CoA2.jpg\n| image_map              = Rosiori de Vede jud Teleorman.png\n| coordinates            = {{coord|44|6|41|N|24|59|39|E|region:RO|display=inline,title}}\n| leader_party           = [[Social Democratic Party (Romania)|PSD]]\n| leader_name            = Valeric\u0103 C\u00e2rciumaru\n| area_total_km2         = \n| website                = {{url|http://www.primariarosioriidevede.ro/}}\n}}\n\n'''Ro\u0219iorii de Vede''' ({{IPA-ro|ro\u0283i\u02ccorij de \u02c8vede}}; sometimes '''Ro\u0219iori de Vede''' or, in old versions, '''Ru\u0219ii de Vede''') is a [[municipiu|city]] in [[Teleorman County]], [[Romania]]. Located in the [[Wallachia]] region, it is one of the oldest cities in the country. It was first mentioned in a document which dates back to 1385, when the city was visited by two [[List of states in the Holy Roman Empire|German]] [[pilgrim]]s who were returning from [[Jerusalem]] and stopped for a few days in a town they called ''Russenart''.{{citation needed|date=December 2010}}\n\nSeveral Romanian personalities were born in and around the city, such as [[Iulian Miu]], [[Radu Gr\u0103m\u0103ticu]], [[Alexandru Dep\u0103r\u0103\u021beanu]], [[Gala Galaction]], [[Petru Bellu]], [[Zaharia Stancu]], [[Marin Preda]] and [[Viorica D\u0103ncil\u0103]].\n\n{{Historical populations\n| source = Census data\n| 1912 |10960\n| 1930 |11453\n| 1948 |14905\n| 1956 |17320\n| 1966 |21747\n| 1977 |28847\n| 1992 |37640\n| 2002 |31873\n| 2011 |24222\n}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Ro\u0219iorii de Vede}}\n* [http://www.primariarosioriidevede.ro/ Ro\u0219iori de Vede City Hall site]\n* [http://www.rosioriidevedeonline.3owl.com/ Ro\u0219iori de Vede Community site]{{dead link|date=April 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n\n{{Teleorman County}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rosiorii De Vede}}\n[[Category:Cities in Romania]]\n[[Category:Populated places in Teleorman County]]\n\n\n{{Teleorman-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Markussep", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ro%C8%99iorii_de_Vede"}
{"title_page": "Richard Sharpe (historian)", "text_new": "{{short description|British historian}}\n'''Richard Sharpe''', {{Post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|sep=,|FBA|FSA|FRHistS}} (17 February 1954 \u2013 21 March 2020)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://doi.org/10.1093/ww/9780199540884.013.U4000410 |title=Sharpe, Prof. Richard |work=Who's Who 2020 |publisher=Oxford University Press |date=2019 |accessdate=23 March 2020 }}{{subscription}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Professor Richard Sharpe (1954-2020) |url=https://www.wadham.ox.ac.uk/news/2020/march/professor-richard-sharpe-1954-2020 |website=Wadham College |publisher=University of Oxford |date=2020-03-23 |access-date=2020-03-23 |archive-url= http://web.archive.org/web/20200323153516/https://www.wadham.ox.ac.uk/news/2020/march/professor-richard-sharpe-1954-2020 |archive-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> was a British historian and academic, who was [[Professor]] of [[Diplomatics|Diplomatic]] at the [[University of Oxford]] and a fellow of [[Wadham College, Oxford]]. His broad interests were the history of medieval [[England]], [[Ireland]], [[Scotland]], and [[Wales]]. He had a special concern with first-hand work on the primary sources of medieval history, including the practices of [[palaeography]], diplomatic and the editorial process, as well as the historical and legal contexts of medieval documents. He was the general editor of the ''Corpus of British Medieval Library Catalogues,'' and editor of a forthcoming edition of the charters of [[Henry I of England|King Henry I of England]].<ref name=OxHist>{{cite web |title=Professor Richard Sharpe |url=https://www.history.ox.ac.uk/people/professor-richard-sharpe |website=University of Oxford History Faculty |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20191208133911/https://www.history.ox.ac.uk/people/professor-richard-sharpe |archivedate=2019-12-08 |accessdate=2020-03-23}}</ref><ref name=OxHistArch>{{cite web |title=Richard Sharpe |url=http://www.history.ox.ac.uk/faculty/staff/profile/sharpe/ |website=University of Oxford History Faculty |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160608134124/http://www.history.ox.ac.uk/faculty/staff/profile/sharpe/index.html |archivedate=2016-06-08}} (Staff profile on former website with links to some publications.)</ref>\n\n==Biography==\n\nStarpe studied at [[St Peter's School, York]] and then took his BA at [[Trinity College, Cambridge]], studying Classics for Part I of the degree and then [[Anglo Saxon, Norse and Celtic]] for Part II, where he studied with, amongst others, [[Simon Keynes]], [[Kathleen Hughes (historian)|Kathleen Hughes]], and [[Michael Lapidge]]. He graduated with a first in 1977, and published his first book, a history of [[Raasay]] the same year.<ref>Thomas Charles-Edwards, '[https://www.history.ox.ac.uk/tribute-professor-richard-sharpe-fba Tribute to Professor Richard Sharpe (1954-2020)]' (2 April 2020).</ref> Sharpe stayed in the ASNaC department for his PhD, on Latin-language Irish hagiography, which was the basis for his 1991 ''Medieval Irish Saints' Lives: an introduction to <nowiki>'</nowiki>Vitae sanctorum Hiberniae<nowiki>'</nowiki>''.<ref name=Wadham>{{cite web |title= Richard Sharpe, Professorial Fellow, Wadham College |website=Wadham College University of Oxford |url= https://www.wadham.ox.ac.uk/people/fellows-and-academic-staff/s/richard-sharpe |archivedate=2020-01-13 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113161021/https://www.wadham.ox.ac.uk/people/fellows-and-academic-staff/s/richard-sharpe |accessdate=2020-03-23}}</ref> From 1981 to 1990, Sharpe was an assistant editor of the ''[[Dictionary of Medieval Latin from British Sources]]''.<ref>Richard Ashdowne, '[https://dmlbs.wordpress.com/2020/03/23/richard-sharpe Richard Sharpe]', ''DMLBS: Dictionary of Medieval Latin from British Sources'' (23 March 2020).</ref>\n\nAs the [[University of Oxford]]'s 2018\u20132019 Lyell Reader in Bibliography, Sharpe delivered that year's [[Lyell Lectures]] on the topic of \"Libraries and Books in Medieval England: The Role of Libraries in a Changing Book Economy\".<ref name=Lyell>{{cite web |title=The Lyell Lectures |website=Centre for the Study of the Book, Bodleian Library, University of Oxford |access-date=2020-03-23 |url=https://www.bodleian.ox.ac.uk/csb/lyell}}</ref><ref name=podcasts_Sharpe>{{cite web |url=http://podcasts.ox.ac.uk/people/richard-sharpe |title=Series featuring Richard Sharpe |website=The Bodleian Libraries BODcasts |publisher=University of Oxford |access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> He was elected a [[Fellow of the British Academy]] (FBA) in 2003,<ref name=BritAcad>{{cite web |website=The British Academy |url= https://www.thebritishacademy.ac.uk/fellows/richard-sharpe-FBA |title= Professor Richard Sharpe FBA |accessdate=2020-03-22 |archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20200322214319/https://www.thebritishacademy.ac.uk/fellows/richard-sharpe-FBA |archivedate=2020-03-22}}</ref> and an [[Honorary Member of the Royal Irish Academy]] in 2018.<ref name=RIA>{{cite web |website=The Royal Irish Academy |url=https://www.ria.ie/news/membership/member-profile-richard-sharpe |title=Member Profile: Richard Sharpe |date=2019-05-30 |accessdate=2020-03-23 |archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20191129215037/https://www.ria.ie/news/membership/member-profile-richard-sharpe |archivedate=2019-11-29}}</ref> In 2020, he was elected a Corresponding Fellow of the [[Medieval Academy of America]].<ref name=MAA>{{cite news |title=MAA News \u2013 MAA Fellows Election Results |url=http://www.themedievalacademyblog.org/maa-news-maa-fellows-election-results/ |accessdate=2020-03-23 |publisher=Medieval Academy of America |date=2020-02-03}}</ref>\n\n==Publications==\n\n;Books as author\n* {{cite book|last1=Sharpe|first1=Richard|title=Raasay: a study in island history|date=1977|publisher=Grant and Cutler|location=London|isbn=978-0-7293-0029-2}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Sharpe|first1=Richard|title=Raasay: A Study in Island History. Documents and Sources, People and Places|date=1978|publisher=Grant and Cutler|location=London|isbn=978-8439965473}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Sharpe|first1=Richard|last2=Lapidge|first2=Michael|title=A bibliography of Celtic-Latin literature 400-1200|series=Royal Irish Academy dictionary of medieval Latin from Celtic sources. Ancillary publications ; 1|date=1985|publisher=Royal Irish Academy|location=Dublin|isbn=0901714437}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Sharpe|first1=Richard|title=Medieval Irish Saints' Lives: an introduction to ''Vitae sanctorum Hiberniae''|date=1991|publisher=Clarendon Press|location=Oxford|isbn=978-0-19-167821-9}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Sharpe|first1=Richard|title=Life of [[Columba|St. Columba]] |date=1991 |publisher=Penguin Books |location=Harmondsworth, Middlesex |isbn=978-0-14-044462-9}}\n* {{Cite book| publisher = British Library| isbn = 0-7123-0336-7| last1 = Sharpe| first1 = Richard| last2 = Carley| first2 = James P.| last3 = Thomson| first3 = Rodney M.| last4 = Watson| first4 = Andrew G.| title = English [[Benedictines|Benedictine]] Libraries: the shorter catalogues| location = London| series = Corpus of British medieval library catalogues| date = 1996}}\n* {{Cite book| publisher = Brepols| isbn = 978-2-503-50575-6| last = Sharpe| first = Richard |title=A Handlist of the Latin Writers of Great Britain and Ireland before 1540| location = Turnhout| series = Publications of the ''Journal of Medieval Latin''| date = 1997}}\n* {{Cite book| publisher = Brepols| isbn = 978-2-503-51258-7| last = Sharpe| first = Richard| title = Titulus: identifying medieval Latin texts. An evidence-based approach| location = Turnhout| series = Brepols essays in European culture| date = 2003}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Sharpe |first1=Richard |title=Norman rule in Cumbria, 1092\u20131136 |date=2006 |publisher=Cumberland and Westmorland Antiquarian and Archaeological Society |isbn=9781873124437 |series=Cumberland and Westmorland Antiquarian and Archaeological Society, Tract Series |volume=21 |place=Kendal}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sharpe, Richard}}\n[[Category:Fellows of Wadham College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:British medievalists]]\n[[Category:English palaeographers]]\n[[Category:1954 births]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the British Academy]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Society of Antiquaries of London]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Historical Society]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n\n{{UK-historian-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British historian}}\n'''Richard Sharpe''', {{Post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|sep=,|FBA|FSA|FRHistS}} (17 February 1954 \u2013 22 March 2020)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://doi.org/10.1093/ww/9780199540884.013.U4000410 |title=Sharpe, Prof. Richard |work=Who's Who 2020 |publisher=Oxford University Press |date=2019 |accessdate=23 March 2020 }}{{subscription}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Professor Richard Sharpe (1954-2020) |url=https://www.wadham.ox.ac.uk/news/2020/march/professor-richard-sharpe-1954-2020 |website=Wadham College |publisher=University of Oxford |date=2020-03-23 |access-date=2020-03-23 |archive-url= http://web.archive.org/web/20200323153516/https://www.wadham.ox.ac.uk/news/2020/march/professor-richard-sharpe-1954-2020 |archive-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> was a British historian and academic, who was [[Professor]] of [[Diplomatics|Diplomatic]] at the [[University of Oxford]] and a fellow of [[Wadham College, Oxford]]. His broad interests were the history of medieval [[England]], [[Ireland]], [[Scotland]], and [[Wales]]. He had a special concern with first-hand work on the primary sources of medieval history, including the practices of [[palaeography]], diplomatic and the editorial process, as well as the historical and legal contexts of medieval documents. He was the general editor of the ''Corpus of British Medieval Library Catalogues,'' and editor of a forthcoming edition of the charters of [[Henry I of England|King Henry I of England]].<ref name=OxHist>{{cite web |title=Professor Richard Sharpe |url=https://www.history.ox.ac.uk/people/professor-richard-sharpe |website=University of Oxford History Faculty |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20191208133911/https://www.history.ox.ac.uk/people/professor-richard-sharpe |archivedate=2019-12-08 |accessdate=2020-03-23}}</ref><ref name=OxHistArch>{{cite web |title=Richard Sharpe |url=http://www.history.ox.ac.uk/faculty/staff/profile/sharpe/ |website=University of Oxford History Faculty |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160608134124/http://www.history.ox.ac.uk/faculty/staff/profile/sharpe/index.html |archivedate=2016-06-08}} (Staff profile on former website with links to some publications.)</ref>\n\n==Biography==\n\nStarpe studied at [[St Peter's School, York]] and then took his BA at [[Trinity College, Cambridge]], studying Classics for Part I of the degree and then [[Anglo Saxon, Norse and Celtic]] for Part II, where he studied with, amongst others, [[Simon Keynes]], [[Kathleen Hughes (historian)|Kathleen Hughes]], and [[Michael Lapidge]]. He graduated with a first in 1977, and published his first book, a history of [[Raasay]] the same year.<ref>Thomas Charles-Edwards, '[https://www.history.ox.ac.uk/tribute-professor-richard-sharpe-fba Tribute to Professor Richard Sharpe (1954-2020)]' (2 April 2020).</ref> Sharpe stayed in the ASNaC department for his PhD, on Latin-language Irish hagiography, which was the basis for his 1991 ''Medieval Irish Saints' Lives: an introduction to <nowiki>'</nowiki>Vitae sanctorum Hiberniae<nowiki>'</nowiki>''.<ref name=Wadham>{{cite web |title= Richard Sharpe, Professorial Fellow, Wadham College |website=Wadham College University of Oxford |url= https://www.wadham.ox.ac.uk/people/fellows-and-academic-staff/s/richard-sharpe |archivedate=2020-01-13 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113161021/https://www.wadham.ox.ac.uk/people/fellows-and-academic-staff/s/richard-sharpe |accessdate=2020-03-23}}</ref> From 1981 to 1990, Sharpe was an assistant editor of the ''[[Dictionary of Medieval Latin from British Sources]]''.<ref>Richard Ashdowne, '[https://dmlbs.wordpress.com/2020/03/23/richard-sharpe Richard Sharpe]', ''DMLBS: Dictionary of Medieval Latin from British Sources'' (23 March 2020).</ref>\n\nAs the [[University of Oxford]]'s 2018\u20132019 Lyell Reader in Bibliography, Sharpe delivered that year's [[Lyell Lectures]] on the topic of \"Libraries and Books in Medieval England: The Role of Libraries in a Changing Book Economy\".<ref name=Lyell>{{cite web |title=The Lyell Lectures |website=Centre for the Study of the Book, Bodleian Library, University of Oxford |access-date=2020-03-23 |url=https://www.bodleian.ox.ac.uk/csb/lyell}}</ref><ref name=podcasts_Sharpe>{{cite web |url=http://podcasts.ox.ac.uk/people/richard-sharpe |title=Series featuring Richard Sharpe |website=The Bodleian Libraries BODcasts |publisher=University of Oxford |access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> He was elected a [[Fellow of the British Academy]] (FBA) in 2003,<ref name=BritAcad>{{cite web |website=The British Academy |url= https://www.thebritishacademy.ac.uk/fellows/richard-sharpe-FBA |title= Professor Richard Sharpe FBA |accessdate=2020-03-22 |archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20200322214319/https://www.thebritishacademy.ac.uk/fellows/richard-sharpe-FBA |archivedate=2020-03-22}}</ref> and an [[Honorary Member of the Royal Irish Academy]] in 2018.<ref name=RIA>{{cite web |website=The Royal Irish Academy |url=https://www.ria.ie/news/membership/member-profile-richard-sharpe |title=Member Profile: Richard Sharpe |date=2019-05-30 |accessdate=2020-03-23 |archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20191129215037/https://www.ria.ie/news/membership/member-profile-richard-sharpe |archivedate=2019-11-29}}</ref> In 2020, he was elected a Corresponding Fellow of the [[Medieval Academy of America]].<ref name=MAA>{{cite news |title=MAA News \u2013 MAA Fellows Election Results |url=http://www.themedievalacademyblog.org/maa-news-maa-fellows-election-results/ |accessdate=2020-03-23 |publisher=Medieval Academy of America |date=2020-02-03}}</ref>\n\n==Publications==\n\n;Books as author\n* {{cite book|last1=Sharpe|first1=Richard|title=Raasay: a study in island history|date=1977|publisher=Grant and Cutler|location=London|isbn=978-0-7293-0029-2}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Sharpe|first1=Richard|title=Raasay: A Study in Island History. Documents and Sources, People and Places|date=1978|publisher=Grant and Cutler|location=London|isbn=978-8439965473}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Sharpe|first1=Richard|last2=Lapidge|first2=Michael|title=A bibliography of Celtic-Latin literature 400-1200|series=Royal Irish Academy dictionary of medieval Latin from Celtic sources. Ancillary publications ; 1|date=1985|publisher=Royal Irish Academy|location=Dublin|isbn=0901714437}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Sharpe|first1=Richard|title=Medieval Irish Saints' Lives: an introduction to ''Vitae sanctorum Hiberniae''|date=1991|publisher=Clarendon Press|location=Oxford|isbn=978-0-19-167821-9}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Sharpe|first1=Richard|title=Life of [[Columba|St. Columba]] |date=1991 |publisher=Penguin Books |location=Harmondsworth, Middlesex |isbn=978-0-14-044462-9}}\n* {{Cite book| publisher = British Library| isbn = 0-7123-0336-7| last1 = Sharpe| first1 = Richard| last2 = Carley| first2 = James P.| last3 = Thomson| first3 = Rodney M.| last4 = Watson| first4 = Andrew G.| title = English [[Benedictines|Benedictine]] Libraries: the shorter catalogues| location = London| series = Corpus of British medieval library catalogues| date = 1996}}\n* {{Cite book| publisher = Brepols| isbn = 978-2-503-50575-6| last = Sharpe| first = Richard |title=A Handlist of the Latin Writers of Great Britain and Ireland before 1540| location = Turnhout| series = Publications of the ''Journal of Medieval Latin''| date = 1997}}\n* {{Cite book| publisher = Brepols| isbn = 978-2-503-51258-7| last = Sharpe| first = Richard| title = Titulus: identifying medieval Latin texts. An evidence-based approach| location = Turnhout| series = Brepols essays in European culture| date = 2003}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Sharpe |first1=Richard |title=Norman rule in Cumbria, 1092\u20131136 |date=2006 |publisher=Cumberland and Westmorland Antiquarian and Archaeological Society |isbn=9781873124437 |series=Cumberland and Westmorland Antiquarian and Archaeological Society, Tract Series |volume=21 |place=Kendal}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sharpe, Richard}}\n[[Category:Fellows of Wadham College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:British medievalists]]\n[[Category:English palaeographers]]\n[[Category:1954 births]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the British Academy]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Society of Antiquaries of London]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Historical Society]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n\n{{UK-historian-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Hibernensis", "label": "safe", "comment": "Day of death corrected from 22 March to 21 March", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Richard_Sharpe_(historian)"}
