{"title_page": "Southend High School for Girls", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=December 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2018}}\n{{Infobox school \n| name          = Southend High School for Girls\n| image         = SHSG.png\n| image_size          = 89x100\n| caption       = \n| motto         = ''Latin'': Ad Dei Gloriam<br />\"Glory to God\", previously \"Vehicula Vehicula Vehicula; Amitae Tuae Prudentiae.\"\n| established   = 1913\n| closed        = \n| type          = [[Grammar school]]<br />[[Academy (English school)|Academy]]\n| religious_affiliation      =  \n| president     = \n| head_label    = Headteacher\n| head          = Mr Carey \n| r_head_label  = \n| r_head        = \n| chair_label   = Chair of Governors\n| chair         = Mr Bacon\n| founder       = \n| specialist    =  \n| address        = [[Southchurch]] Boulevard\n| city          = [[Southend-on-Sea]]\n| county        = [[Essex]]\n| country       = England\n| postcode      = SS2 4UZ\n| local_authority           =  \n| dfeno         = 882/5428\n| urn           = 136444\n| ofsted        = Yes\n| staff         = \n| enrolment    = \n| gender        = Girls\n| lower_age     = 11\n| upper_age     = 18\n| houses        = {{colour box|red}} Artemis<br />{{colour box|blue}} Hermes<br />{{colour box|yellow}} Hera<br />{{colour box|purple}} Athene<br />{{colour box|white}} Aphrodite<br />{{colour box|orange}} Aurora\n| colours       = Green and white\n| publication   =  \n| free_label_1  =  \n| free_1        =  \n| free_label_2  = \n| free_2        = \n| free_label_3  = \n| free_3        = \n| website       = http://www.shsg.org/\n}}\n\n'''Southend High School for Girls''' is a grammar school with [[Academy (English school)|academy status]] situated on [[Southchurch]] Boulevard in the east of [[Southend-on-Sea]], Essex, England. It caters for students from the age of 11 through to 18 years old.\n\n==Academics==\nThe school achieved an 'Outstanding' grade following a full [[Ofsted]] inspection in December 2011. The school was rated as outstanding in all 31 areas, one of fewer than 50 secondary schools nationally to be so assessed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ofsted.gov.uk/inspection-reports/find-inspection-report/provider/ELS/136444 |title=Find an inspection report |publisher=Ofsted|date=14 January 2012 |accessdate=14 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nSouthend High School for Girls has a specialism in languages. All [[Key Stage 3]] students study French and German or French and Spanish (replacing Latin in 2002, which is now available as an additional subject studied off-timetable).\n\nSimilar to other Southend-on-Sea district grammar schools, the school achieves excellent results at [[Advanced Level (UK)|A level]] and various other examinations which are consistently above national averages, in part because of the selective entry system.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/shared/bsp/hi/education/09/school_tables/secondary_schools/html/882_5428.stm |title=Performance results for Southend High School for Girls |work=BBC News|date=13 January 2010 |accessdate=29 July 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn Science, Mathematics, English and Geography all students take a two-year Key Stage 3 qualification allowing them to commence their [[GCSE]] studies early.\n\n==Demographics==\nAccording to the school's most recent [[Ofsted]] report:\n\"Most students are from a [[White British]] heritage, and a broadly average proportion is from minority ethnic backgrounds. No students are in the early stages of learning English. The proportion of students with special educational needs and/or disabilities is low and the proportion known to be entitled to free school meals is below average.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://reports.ofsted.gov.uk/provider/files/1988683/urn/136444.pdf |title=Southend High School for Girls inspection report |publisher=Ofsted |date=12 December 2011 |accessdate=6 March 2015 }}{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==Sports==\n{{Unreferenced section|date=July 2016}}\nThe school competes in various sports, including football and cross country running. Recently {{when|date=July 2016}} girls have been given the opportunity to represent the school in show-jumping. Sports Day is a chance for the athletic girls to win Sports Day titles. Each house competes in a range of events such as shot put, javelin, sprinting and hurdles. In more recent years the school underwent a major extension providing it with a new and fully equipped sports hall. (this wasn't recently)\n\nThe school represented England in the World Schools' Athletics in Tallinn in 2009 and came third and took part in the World Schools' Athletics Championships in Prague 2013 and finished in 5th place.\n\nSouthend High School for Girls has won the junior girls National Athletics title on 13 occasions, the summer of 2016 being the 13th title. The school also holds the record for being crowned Junior Champions the most times of any other school entering the competition. The school has also won the intermediate girls title on 5 occasions, the last time was in 2016 also.\n\nSouthend High School for Girls has also won the Junior Girls National Cross Country Cup twice (1985 and 2010) and the Intermediate Girls National Cross Country Cup title in 2011 and 2012.\n\n==Houses==\nSouthend High School For Girls has 6 houses. Before 2016 there were only 5 houses, Artemis \u2013 Red, Hermes \u2013 Blue, Hera \u2013 Yellow, Athene \u2013 Purple, Aphrodite \u2013 White (but wear pink on sports day). It was not until 2016 a new house, Aurora \u2013 Orange, was added to make up with the added form groups in year 7 and 8.\n\n==Notable former pupils==\n{{see also|Category:People educated at Southend High School for Girls}}\n* Prof [[Deborah Ashby]], Professor of Medical Statistics and Clinical Trials at Imperial College London and expert on Bayesian statistics\n* Prof [[Lorna Casselton]], Professor of Fungal Genetics at the [[University of Oxford]] and expert in the sexual behaviour of mushrooms<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oxfordmail.co.uk/news/community/obituaries/obits/11137596.Professor_conducted_studies_into_sexual_behaviour_of_mushrooms/ | title= Professor conducted studies into sexual behaviour of mushrooms|work=Oxford Mail|date=2014-04-10 |accessdate=2014-08-27}}</ref> from 1997 to 2003\n* [[Brigadier]] Jill Field CBE, Matron-in-Chief of the Army and Director of [[Defence Nursing Services]] from 1989 to 1992\n* [[Jo Richardson]], Labour MP for [[Barking (UK Parliament constituency)|Barking]] from 1974 to 1994\n* [[Rachel Riley]], co-host of ''[[Countdown (game show)|Countdown]]'' from 2009.<ref>{{cite web|author=Ian Gallagher |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/tvshowbiz/article-1088651/Rachel-Rileys-Countdown-coolest-maths-job-world.html |title=Rachel Riley's Countdown to 'the coolest maths job in the world' |work=Daily Mail.ukdate=23 November 2008 |accessdate=29 July 2011}}</ref>\n* [[Sarah Wilhelmy]], Former Great Britain international Athlete and representative at the [[2000 Summer Olympics]]\n\n==Arson==\nIn April 2003 the school was closed for two days following a fire in an art room started by a student.<ref>[http://archive.echo-news.co.uk/2003/4/29/146899.html ]{{dead link|date=July 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/essex/2982975.stm |title=School fire 'may be arson' |work=BBC News|date=29 April 2003 |accessdate=29 July 2011}}</ref> On the day of the re-opening another fire was started; eventually three students were arrested in connection with the incidents.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/essex/3050141.stm |title=Three arrests in school arson case |work=BBC News|date=22 May 2003 |accessdate=29 July 2011}}</ref> There was also another fire started in Room 8 on the middle floor of the towerblock where the students set a record for the amount of time taken to leave the building. The second fire was started in close proximity to gas pipes. In total three fires were started in the space of a single month leading to several parents withdrawing their daughters from the school.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.echo-news.co.uk/archive/2003/05/02/5454379.Southend__School_fire_heightens_arson_fear/|title=Southend: School fire heightens arson fear|last=|first=|date=2 May 2003|website=Echo|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402123516/http://www.echo-news.co.uk/archive/2003/05/02/5454379.Southend__School_fire_heightens_arson_fear/|archivedate=2 April 2015|accessdate=6 March 2015}}</ref>\n\t \nThe school was again attacked in December 2005 causing several thousand pounds worth of damage to the school kitchen and a number of classrooms at the front of the school. Despite the then headteacher David Mansfield's strong rhetoric,<ref>[http://archive.echo-news.co.uk/2005/12/28/235340.html ]{{dead link|date=July 2011}}</ref> the damage was so extensive that the Christmas holiday break was extended for students of years 7 and 8.<ref>[http://archive.echo-news.co.uk/2006/1/3/235441.html ]{{dead link|date=July 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"news.bbc.co.uk\">{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/essex/4578930.stm |title=Suspected arson at girls school |work=BBC News|date=3 January 2006 |accessdate=29 July 2011}}</ref> Reconstruction work took almost a year whilst a new kitchen, dining room and reception area were constructed and a number of classrooms had to be fully refitted.<ref name=\"news.bbc.co.uk\"/><ref>[http://www.southend.gov.uk/news/default.asp?id=1718 ]{{dead link|date=July 2011}}</ref>\n\nAnd no one tells us aout these things... shame\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|http://www.shsg.org}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20081206064020/http://www.edubase.gov.uk/establishment/summary.xhtml EduBase]\n\n{{Schools in Southend-on-Sea}}\n{{coord|51.5415|0.7459|type:edu_region:GB-SOS|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1913]]\n[[Category:Grammar schools in Southend-on-Sea]]\n[[Category:Girls' schools in Essex]]\n[[Category:Academies in Southend-on-Sea]]\n[[Category:1913 establishments in England]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=December 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2018}}\n{{Infobox school \n| name          = Southend High School for Girls\n| image         = SHSG.png\n| image_size          = 89x100\n| caption       = \n| motto         = ''Latin'': Ad Dei Gloriam<br />\"Glory to God\", previously \"Vehicula Vehicula Vehicula; Amitae Tuae Prudentiae.\"\n| established   = 1913\n| closed        = \n| type          = [[Grammar school]]<br />[[Academy (English school)|Academy]]\n| religious_affiliation      =  \n| president     = \n| head_label    = Headteacher\n| head          = Mr Carey \n| r_head_label  = \n| r_head        = \n| chair_label   = Chair of Governors\n| chair         = Mr Bacon\n| founder       = \n| specialist    =  \n| address        = [[Southchurch]] Boulevard\n| city          = [[Southend-on-Sea]]\n| county        = [[Essex]]\n| country       = England\n| postcode      = SS2 4UZ\n| local_authority           =  \n| dfeno         = 882/5428\n| urn           = 136444\n| ofsted        = Yes\n| staff         = \n| enrolment    = \n| gender        = Girls\n| lower_age     = 11\n| upper_age     = 18\n| houses        = {{colour box|red}} Artemis<br />{{colour box|blue}} Hermes<br />{{colour box|yellow}} Hera<br />{{colour box|purple}} Athene<br />{{colour box|white}} Aphrodite<br />{{colour box|orange}} Aurora\n| colours       = Green and white\n| publication   =  \n| free_label_1  =  \n| free_1        =  \n| free_label_2  = \n| free_2        = \n| free_label_3  = \n| free_3        = \n| website       = http://www.shsg.org/\n}}\n\n'''Southend High School for Girls''' is a grammar school with [[Academy (English school)|academy status]] situated on [[Southchurch]] Boulevard in the east of [[Southend-on-Sea]], Essex, England. It caters for students from the age of 11 through to 18 years o